  "footnotes": [
    "Zhangzhung Kingdom (c.500 BCE – 625 CE): Pre-Buddhist civilisation of western Tibet centred around Mount Kailash. The Bon religion originated here. Conquered and absorbed by the Tibetan Empire under Songtsen Gampo.",
    "Tibetan Empire (c.618–842): Founded by Songtsen Gampo, who unified the Tibetan plateau, adopted Buddhism, and created the Tibetan script. Trisong Detsen expanded the empire to its greatest extent, sacking the Tang capital Chang'an in 763. The Pugyal dynasty collapsed after the assassination of Lang Darma (842), fragmenting Tibet for four centuries.",
    "Guge Kingdom (c.842–1630): Western Tibetan kingdom that played a crucial role in the 'Second Diffusion' of Buddhism in Tibet. Rinchen Zangpo translated numerous Sanskrit texts. The kingdom was destroyed by the Ladakhi-Mughal alliance.",
    "Ganden Phodrang (1642–1959): The Tibetan government established by the 5th Dalai Lama with Mongol (Khoshut) military backing. The 'Great Fifth' Dalai Lama built the Potala Palace and unified Tibet under Gelug school authority. The Qing dynasty established the Amban (resident commissioner) system after intervening against Dzungar invasions (1720).",
    "Dzungar Khanate: The last great nomadic empire of Central Asia. The Dzungars invaded Tibet in 1717, deposing the 6th Dalai Lama's regent. The Qing Kangxi Emperor's counter-invasion (1720) expelled the Dzungars and established permanent Qing suzerainty over Tibet.",
    "Younghusband Expedition (1903–1904): British military expedition to Tibet led by Colonel Francis Younghusband, forcing the Treaty of Lhasa (1904). The 13th Dalai Lama fled to Mongolia and then China. This event triggered the Qing's belated attempts to assert direct control over Tibet.",
    "Tibet since 1950: The PRC's People's Liberation Army entered Tibet in 1950. The 1959 Tibetan uprising was crushed, and the 14th Dalai Lama fled to India, establishing a government-in-exile in Dharamsala. The Cultural Revolution (1966–76) destroyed thousands of monasteries. Tibet remains one of the most contested sovereignty disputes in Asia."
  ]
